00:00:57.520 --> 00:00:59.880
at a site called West Heslerton.

00:00:59.880 --> 00:01:03.270
West Heslerton is an enormously
complex multi-period chunk

00:01:03.270 --> 00:01:06.227
of landscape, and it's produced
over a million artifacts.

00:01:06.227 --> 00:01:07.810
And I know that's
one of those numbers

00:01:07.810 --> 00:01:10.400
that Google doesn't count
that low, but in archeology

00:01:10.400 --> 00:01:12.850
that's a very, very big number.

00:01:12.850 --> 00:01:15.330
In his 30 years of dealing
with West Heslerton,

00:01:15.330 --> 00:01:18.340
Dominic has pioneered a whole
gamut of digital methods

00:01:18.340 --> 00:01:21.850
in archeology, which are now
absolutely standard practice,

00:01:21.850 --> 00:01:24.130
including remote
sensing, the collection

00:01:24.130 --> 00:01:27.989
integration and analysis of
geospatial data, 3D imaging,

00:01:27.989 --> 00:01:30.280
as well as all sorts of
interesting things like the use

00:01:30.280 --> 00:01:32.480
of isotopes and DNA.

00:01:32.480 --> 00:01:35.330
And the last important thing
to know about Dominic before he

00:01:35.330 --> 00:01:37.240
comes up is that
he's been excavating

00:01:37.240 --> 00:01:38.920
since he was 11 years old.

00:01:38.920 --> 00:01:42.050
And one doesn't get to hear
of an archeology prodigy

00:01:42.050 --> 00:01:45.872
very often, and I think
he might be the only one.

